the University of Maryland.

00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:24.190 position:56%
So please talk to Karen Kohn Bradley
if you're interested in attending

00:01:24.190 --> 00:01:28.060
and finding out more about it,
but please join everyone there

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:30.380
if you don't have any plans.

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:32.580
I'm certainly going to be there.

00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:38.550 position:56%
The event today is also part of an
ongoing lecture series that we have,

00:01:38.550 --> 00:01:41.630
the Benjamin A. Botkin
lecture series.

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:45.580
And this is a series that allows
the American Folk Life Center

00:01:45.580 --> 00:01:50.600
to present the latest and
best scholarship in folklore

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:55.030
at the musicology, cultural
studies and the like.

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:58.110
And it accomplishes two purchases.

00:01:58.110 --> 00:02:02.890
The first, sharing all of this
great research and information,

00:02:02.890 --> 00:02:05.930
but it also allows us to
enrich our own collections.

00:02:05.930 --> 00:02:10.240
And in fact, the conversation
that we're going to be privvy

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:14.210
to over the next couple
of hours will be recorded

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:19.230
and put online eventually available
to people throughout the world

00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:22.310 position:56%
and to people in future generations.

00:02:22.310 --> 00:02:27.460
So with that said, let me ask you
