00:09:35.130 --> 00:09:39.500
&gt;&gt; Forrestine Paulay: I think
I'll start since I started.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:46.970
Oh, wow. Alan Lomax was a
student of Ray Birdwhistell.

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:57.640
And when Alan had already developed
the countermetric study, he --

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:00.130
there were certain
questions that he had

00:10:00.130 --> 00:10:04.560
that he felt he wasn't
finding the answers

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:08.470
for in the countermetric study.

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:11.970
So he spoke with Birdwhistell,
Ray Birdwhistell, about this --

00:10:11.970 --> 00:10:15.490
Ray Birdwhistell was
the founder of kinesics.

00:10:15.490 --> 00:10:20.810
And Birdwhistell said, "Well,
dance is a more fundamental,

00:10:20.810 --> 00:10:25.100
more primary relative
expression than song.

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:28.140
And if you're going to find out
the answers to the questions

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:32.710
that you're interested in, you're
going to need to look at dance.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:37.720
And Birdwhistell recommended
[inaudible] analysis

00:10:37.720 --> 00:10:45.960
as probably the most appropriate
analysis for discovering the kinds

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:50.730
of answers to the questions
that Alan had.

00:10:50.730 --> 00:10:54.040
So Alan called up -- I guess

00:10:54.040 --> 00:11:00.490
at that point it was the Dance
Notation Bureau and invited Irmgard

00:11:00.490 --> 00:11:07.220
and as a dancer, Irmgard asked
me to come along with her

00:11:07.220 --> 00:11:11.520 position:56%
in this interview with Alan to begin

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:18.070
to discuss whether we thought we
could help him develop a system

00:11:18.070 --> 00:11:21.850
for looking at movement
cross culturally.

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:28.750
It turned out to be an extremely
interesting experience at that time

00:11:28.750 --> 00:11:32.230
because we were looking from
the [inaudible] analysis point

00:11:32.230 --> 00:11:35.610
of view pretty much at individuals.

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:39.510
And this was not going
to answer the questions

00:11:39.510 --> 00:11:41.690
that Alan was interested in.

00:11:41.690 --> 00:11:45.510
And I can remember that one of the
very first films that we looked

00:11:45.510 --> 00:11:48.290
at with the Georgia
Sea Island Dancers,

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:51.140
and Irmgard and I just had a ball.

00:11:51.140 --> 00:11:54.500
We had such fun getting the
individual differences of everyone

00:11:54.500 --> 00:11:58.350
of the performers, and we
were very excited about this.

00:11:58.350 --> 00:12:03.140
And we bring it in to conference
with Alan, and we start talking

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:06.060
about all these differences,
and Alan sort of sits back,

00:12:06.060 --> 00:12:14.090
and he said something like, "Well,
that doesn't tell us anything."

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:20.220
And we were just totally
off the mark.

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:30.920
And that began a whole education
for both Irmgard and me in looking

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:34.090
at movement in terms
of dfiferent levels.

00:12:34.090 --> 00:12:38.120 position:56%
And that if we're going to look
cross culturally, we are not looking

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:39.860
at individual differences.

00:12:39.860 --> 00:12:44.290
We are not looking at individual --
God, I was just reading something

00:12:44.290 --> 00:12:47.880
out there which was
showing the effort shape --

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:51.480
well, not the shape because
that wasn't in there yet,

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:58.640
the effort graph and
changes from free flow

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:01.900
into bound flow light,
back to free flow.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:04.650
Well, this is not going to make --

00:13:04.650 --> 00:13:07.080
give you any information
that's going

00:13:07.080 --> 00:13:09.850
to enlighten you about cultures.

00:13:09.850 --> 00:13:11.170
All right?

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:16.450
So that began this whole
education of looking

00:13:16.450 --> 00:13:18.300
at the whole world of dance.

00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:24.020
And one of the first things we
did was collect together reels

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:30.170
that had all of the areas
represented, and looking at that

00:13:30.170 --> 00:13:33.350
and beginning to find patterns.

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:39.600
And so the early coding system
came out of that work of looking

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:44.430
across all the different
areas and finding a way

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:52.330
of adapting the Lavon work
to the cultural level.

00:13:52.330 --> 00:13:56.650
That was work that preceded
probably up until 1970.

00:13:56.650 --> 00:13:59.010
So it was very based
in Lavon's work.

00:13:59.010 --> 00:14:03.330
1970, Irmgard went back to
the Dance Notation Bureau

00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:05.480
and began teaching there, and Alan

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:08.620
and I continued working
on the coding system.

00:14:08.620 --> 00:14:11.680
And that was when we began
looking at and brought

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:18.960
into the system patterns of
social organization and also

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:25.990
such parameters as palm
presentation, use of foot.

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:29.500
So we began to look at how
the body was used generally.

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:34.210
So not specifically oriented
to the Lavon background.

00:14:34.210 --> 00:14:37.690
But clearly influenced
by the sensitivity

00:14:37.690 --> 00:14:46.840 position:56%
that a trained person develops by
going through that kind of training.

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:50.670
So that's the beginning.

