00:37:53.750 --> 00:37:55.920
of the coding system,
social organization

00:37:55.920 --> 00:37:58.490
and body presentation and such.

00:37:58.490 --> 00:38:02.580
And at that point I was
handling all of getting the films

00:38:02.580 --> 00:38:07.170
and bringing them in and
selecting the sections,

00:38:07.170 --> 00:38:10.830
and this is finally
when Mary arrived.

00:38:10.830 --> 00:38:16.600
It was marvelous to have another
person there to begin training

00:38:16.600 --> 00:38:20.480
to do some of the coding and to
handle because he was starting

00:38:20.480 --> 00:38:27.590
to handle this -- because it was
one enormous job was collecting all

00:38:27.590 --> 00:38:29.280
the material.

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:32.990
And that was when I was in
the archive just earlier

00:38:32.990 --> 00:38:40.550
and saw my hand notes on have
we called so and so and ask Alan

00:38:40.550 --> 00:38:45.030
if we can spend $150 on this
particular film from so and so.

00:38:45.030 --> 00:38:50.400
And it was a massive job
collecting this footage.

00:38:50.400 --> 00:38:51.700
It really was.

00:38:51.700 --> 00:38:53.530
And we had to go through it,
and then we had to select

00:38:53.530 --> 00:38:56.100
out sections that were
most relevant.

00:38:56.100 --> 00:38:59.330
And the other thing that shaped
the coding system that was

00:38:59.330 --> 00:39:07.440
so fascinating was it was to find
characteristics which you look

00:39:07.440 --> 00:39:10.110
at a small piece of
it, and you've got it.

00:39:10.110 --> 00:39:13.490
In other words, so you're not
having to look and detail this

00:39:13.490 --> 00:39:16.380
and then come up with a code.

00:39:16.380 --> 00:39:20.070
But it has to be conveyed
immediately

00:39:20.070 --> 00:39:21.670
because what we're looking

00:39:21.670 --> 00:39:26.450
at basically is how cultures
represent themselves.

00:39:26.450 --> 00:39:29.330
We're looking at cultural identity.

00:39:29.330 --> 00:39:33.790
And cultural identity has
got to be there right away.

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:38.500
You come up to a person and you
recognize am I of this culture?

00:39:38.500 --> 00:39:41.410
That takes care of a lot of
things and then you can go

00:39:41.410 --> 00:39:44.170
on with other kind of
detailed interaction.

00:39:44.170 --> 00:39:48.160
So we had to shape
our way of looking

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:51.020
to capture cultural identity.

00:39:51.020 --> 00:39:52.870
So it's an interesting thing.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:55.530
One of the things that I've noticed
that certain people have talked

00:39:55.530 --> 00:39:59.710
about is -- oh, because we were
also looking at every day movement

00:39:59.710 --> 00:40:01.530
because we wanted to
see the correlations

00:40:01.530 --> 00:40:05.070
between the dance style
and movement.

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:12.000 position:56%
And there's a real one aspect of the
relationship between the dance style

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:16.000
and the work is that the --

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:17.750
basically this is what
people are doing.

00:40:17.750 --> 00:40:21.840
The neurological patterns are
developed from very early on.

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:25.280
And those are brought
forward in the dance.

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:28.800
But there's another aspect
to it and this is identity.

00:40:28.800 --> 00:40:30.970
And it's cultural identity.

00:40:30.970 --> 00:40:35.020
And that sets the motion
for interaction

00:40:35.020 --> 00:40:37.660
and patterns of interaction.

00:40:37.660 --> 00:40:39.120
So we were looking.

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:42.070
Can you grasp those things?

00:40:42.070 --> 00:40:46.600
So immediately and in ways
that can be taught easily

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:48.680
because we did consensus studies.

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:52.070
Did we do those -- did you cover or
have we already done some of the --

00:40:52.070 --> 00:40:53.370
we had already done those.

00:40:53.370 --> 00:40:55.560
Okay. We were doing
consensus studies.

00:40:55.560 --> 00:41:00.490
So we would bring in students
and teach them some of the lines

00:41:00.490 --> 00:41:07.460
and see worthy parameters
that we had developed.

00:41:07.460 --> 00:41:12.960
Not only did they provide
interesting information in terms

00:41:12.960 --> 00:41:15.150
of the distribution of cultures

00:41:15.150 --> 00:41:18.700
but were these lines
teachable and easily teachable.

00:41:18.700 --> 00:41:22.520
Could other people besides
trained people see them?

00:41:22.520 --> 00:41:27.500
And that also determined
what we kept in the system.

00:41:27.500 --> 00:41:28.800
&gt;&gt; Miriam Phillips: Great.

00:41:28.800 --> 00:41:33.910
Ask you more of my
questions another time,

00:41:33.910 --> 00:41:36.340
but I'm going to keep
the conversation moving.

