00:43:53.430 --> 00:43:59.880
&gt;&gt; Miriam Phillips: Tell us a
little bit about the findings.

00:43:59.880 --> 00:44:02.030
I mean, I'm really curious.

00:44:02.030 --> 00:44:07.100
Did you have -- can you
recall like an aha moment?

00:44:07.100 --> 00:44:10.540
I'm sure you had many aha moments.

00:44:13.090 --> 00:44:18.710
Or, well, I'll let you
[inaudible] that one.

00:44:18.710 --> 00:44:21.560
&gt;&gt; Forrestine Paulay: Yeah, yeah.

00:44:21.560 --> 00:44:38.970
There were -- I mean -- it was
such an education in anthropology.

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:45.880
I mean, coming out from
the perspective of a dance,

00:44:45.880 --> 00:45:02.060
choreographer, it was a constant
source of almost like wonder

00:45:02.060 --> 00:45:11.030
that the use of the body
or the use of space related

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:15.760
in say some instances
to technology so that --

00:45:15.760 --> 00:45:21.120
I mean, the one dimensionality
being related to a particular kind

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:25.230
of tool used that if you're
using say a wooden tool,

00:45:25.230 --> 00:45:32.410
if you were to use it with a
curve, you would probably break it.

00:45:32.410 --> 00:45:40.080
And so watching Australian
aborigines working on say a tree

00:45:40.080 --> 00:45:45.780
with a wooden tool, and the kind of
patience and the kind of repetition

00:45:45.780 --> 00:45:51.470 position:56%
that was required with those
reversing one dimensional movements,

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:58.420
right, in contrast to where they
had metal and seeing the sweep

00:45:58.420 --> 00:46:02.430
of the metal blade
cutting the harvest

00:46:02.430 --> 00:46:07.370
and seeing how this
really did shape the dance.

00:46:07.370 --> 00:46:12.550
I think it's just really seeing
the significance of that that was

00:46:12.550 --> 00:46:22.790
so impressive and I mean, the fact
that would be one level of aha.

00:46:22.790 --> 00:46:28.120
But another level of aha would
be to see the distribution

00:46:28.120 --> 00:46:31.430
of a particular pattern
-- say the one unit torso,

00:46:31.430 --> 00:46:35.140 position:56%
and to see that across the whole
pacific and see it going all the way

00:46:35.140 --> 00:46:40.260
down right into the
tip of South America.

00:46:40.260 --> 00:46:45.430
Or to see that in the use of
horses, it's not only in the use

00:46:45.430 --> 00:46:49.940
of the stirrup but where
there's no stirrups,

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:54.140
where it's basically at
the tip of Patagonia.

00:46:54.140 --> 00:46:55.910
I think it's the [inaudible].

00:46:55.910 --> 00:47:00.510
Interesting how things
start coming back.

00:47:00.510 --> 00:47:05.520
I think it's the [inaudible]
indians who dance on [inaudible].

00:47:05.520 --> 00:47:09.840
They are a horse culture
that was so indomitable

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:13.160
that I think they were
maybe the one cultures

00:47:13.160 --> 00:47:19.080
that was never taken over,
was never by Europeans.

00:47:19.080 --> 00:47:22.780
And they danced on [inaudible].

00:47:22.780 --> 00:47:24.080
American indians.

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:25.380
Not the [inaudible].

00:47:25.380 --> 00:47:28.180
The importance of horses, and
you take that and you think

00:47:28.180 --> 00:47:31.620
of the Georgian dancers
who are dancing on toe.

00:47:31.620 --> 00:47:38.680
So there's something besides
the actual movement patterns

00:47:38.680 --> 00:47:42.260
that are being conveyed
through the dance.

00:47:42.260 --> 00:47:50.030
But there is an identity with
horses and meaningfulness of horses

00:47:50.030 --> 00:47:55.580
where the use of the foot
is like the use of a hoof.

00:47:55.580 --> 00:47:59.910
So it shows something more about
the complexity that we're looking

00:47:59.910 --> 00:48:03.250
at when we're looking at a dance

00:48:03.250 --> 00:48:06.920
because it isn't just these
are the movement patterns

00:48:06.920 --> 00:48:12.470
that the culture survived on,
but these are the identifications

00:48:12.470 --> 00:48:16.940
that these people made with
those things that are important

00:48:16.940 --> 00:48:21.250
in their lives which adds
another level of richness.

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:25.010
And it adds another level of
richness for dance teachers

00:48:25.010 --> 00:48:30.090
to understand when you're working
what's the cultural identity

00:48:30.090 --> 00:48:34.830
like for the person you're
teaching and you're working with?

00:48:34.830 --> 00:48:38.560
And how do you -- how do you teach?

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:42.180
How do you use this choreometrics?

00:48:42.180 --> 00:48:50.140
In order to help people really
experience a shift in identity,

00:48:50.140 --> 00:48:54.290
a shift in cultural identity,
what can you do through movement

00:48:54.290 --> 00:48:57.780
which means drawing on your other
kinds of backgrounds in movement,

00:48:57.780 --> 00:49:04.430
to bring to the dancers so they
can actually experience oh,

00:49:04.430 --> 00:49:07.920
if you start working through the
feet, you're going to get something

00:49:07.920 --> 00:49:10.710
in the upper body that
if you go directly

00:49:10.710 --> 00:49:13.950
to the upper body you're not
going to get because so often

00:49:13.950 --> 00:49:17.700
and what we see, say why
it looks so different

00:49:17.700 --> 00:49:26.460
to see the early Caucasians doing
multiunit style and why it looks

00:49:26.460 --> 00:49:30.070
so stiff, look at their feet.

00:49:30.070 --> 00:49:32.330 position:56%
You've got to work through the feet.

00:49:32.330 --> 00:49:36.710
You have the whole barefootness,
all right, that goes along

00:49:36.710 --> 00:49:38.200
with the multiunit style.

00:49:38.200 --> 00:49:42.420
And it's because the flow comes
from the foot all the way up.

00:49:42.420 --> 00:49:46.510
And if you put a shoe on that foot,
and you don't teach that person,

00:49:46.510 --> 00:49:48.570
you know, you can't go
even if you're barefoot

00:49:48.570 --> 00:49:52.560
as if you have shoes on, you're
not going to get the fluidity

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:54.330
in the multiunitness of the body.

00:49:54.330 --> 00:49:58.890 position:56%
I think I may have went off a little
bit from that, but the question --

00:49:58.890 --> 00:50:00.190
&gt;&gt; Miriam Phillips: Interesting.

00:50:00.190 --> 00:50:04.370
Let me ask Mary something
about the work process,

00:50:04.370 --> 00:50:08.130
and then I have two more
questions and I want to open it up.

00:50:08.130 --> 00:50:16.690
So you're observing, you're doing
-- when the coding sheets came on,

00:50:16.690 --> 00:50:19.170
you're doing the coding sheets.

