00:52:54.470 --> 00:52:57.900
&gt;&gt; Miriam Phillips:
Now, at some point,

00:52:57.900 --> 00:53:04.410
there was some interpretations of
all the patterns that were started

00:53:04.410 --> 00:53:12.520
to be made and once the -- I guess
it was the film started coming out

00:53:12.520 --> 00:53:16.720
and publications, there
was some controversies

00:53:16.720 --> 00:53:18.940
that came up with the project.

00:53:18.940 --> 00:53:22.850
Were you -- did they come
into your conversations?

00:53:22.850 --> 00:53:27.060
And that will be coming
up over the next few days,

00:53:27.060 --> 00:53:29.050
I think, in some conversations.

00:53:29.050 --> 00:53:34.940
But did those come back to
you in the conversations?

00:53:34.940 --> 00:53:37.610
&gt;&gt; Meriam Lobel: I could say
something because at the time

00:53:37.610 --> 00:53:42.340
that I started working there, the
field of anthropology was changing

00:53:42.340 --> 00:53:45.690
and anthropologists felt
that they really needed

00:53:45.690 --> 00:53:50.370
to specialize very much in one
specific culture and perhaps

00:53:50.370 --> 00:53:53.330
in one specific village
within one country.

00:53:53.330 --> 00:53:58.200
And so I always felt there
was a lot of resentment.

00:53:58.200 --> 00:54:01.380
I don't know if that's the
right word, but people didn't

00:54:01.380 --> 00:54:06.370
like the fact that Alan thought
that he could look an objective way

00:54:06.370 --> 00:54:08.520
at a bigger global picture.

00:54:08.520 --> 00:54:10.950
And it really didn't
-- from what I heard,

00:54:10.950 --> 00:54:13.880
it really didn't even have
anything to do with knowledge

00:54:13.880 --> 00:54:15.860
of what the project
was actually doing.

00:54:15.860 --> 00:54:20.460
It was the fact that he was saying
that it was possible to look

00:54:20.460 --> 00:54:23.130
at the world of dance
in a global way.

00:54:23.130 --> 00:54:28.130
And I disagreed with the people
who felt that it was not possible.

00:54:28.130 --> 00:54:32.930
I think his intellectual
capacity and his vision

00:54:32.930 --> 00:54:39.160
and his thoroughness -- it was just
so huge that he could do something

00:54:39.160 --> 00:54:43.130
and I think he gave all of
us tools that we can utilize

00:54:43.130 --> 00:54:48.000
to help us all understand
each other and the ways

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:52.360
that we organize socially
in different types of groups

00:54:52.360 --> 00:54:54.800
and the way that we move and
the way we use our bodies.

00:54:54.800 --> 00:54:57.380
But I think it was very
much a trend of othe times.

00:54:57.380 --> 00:55:02.200
In all kinds of science, of
course, there were people --

00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:07.620
there was a time when
